1.Box Plot

  • Draw a box plot using PlantGrowth dataset.
  • labs() function is to add title, axis labels, and caption.
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight',
       x = 'Group',
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 20))

2. Swap X and Y Axes

  • Turns the box plot sideways with coord_flip()
ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = 'Weight vs Group',
       x = 'Group',
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 20))

3. Arrange two plots side by side

  • Adds a title for both plots using grid.arrange()
library(gridExtra)

p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight',
       x = 'Group',
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 20))
  
p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = 'Weight vs Group',
       x = 'Group',
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 20))
  
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
top = 'Arrange two plots side by side')

4. Setting the Range of a Continious Axis

  • Uses ylim() to set the range
p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight',
       x = 'Group',
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 20))
  
p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  ylim(0, max(PlantGrowth$weight))
  labs(title = 'Weight vs Group',
       x = 'Group',
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 20))
NULL
  grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
top = 'Setting the Range of a Continuous Axes')

5. Reversing a Continuous Axes

  • Flips the y-axis upside down with scale_y_reverse()
p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

p3 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  ylim(6.5, 3.5) +
  labs(title = 'Group vs Weight', 
       x = 'Group', 
       y = 'Weight',
       caption = 'By Valencia, DV, THU, 2024') +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
Scale for y is already present.
Adding another scale for y, which will replace the existing scale.
grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 3,
             top = 'Reversing a Continuous Axis')

6.Setting the Scaling Ratio of the X- and Y-Axes

  • Uses coord_fixed() to keep the proportions equal
  • Makes a scatter plot with the same size for x and y axes
library(gcookbook)  

plot1 <- ggplot(marathon, aes(x=Half,y=Full)) +
  geom_point() 

plot2 <- ggplot(marathon, aes(x=Half,y=Full)) +
  geom_point() +
  coord_fixed() 

grid.arrange(plot1, plot2, ncol=2, 
             top = 'Setting the Scaling Ratio of the X- and Y-Axes')

8.Setting the Positions of Tick Marks

  • Using scale_y_continuous(breaks = â¦) to add specific marks to the y-axis, like 4, 5, and 6
p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot()

p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(4, 4.25, 4.5, 5, 6, 8))

# Add title
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
             top = 'Setting the Positions of Tick Marks')

9.Removing Tick Marks and Labels

  • Hides the y-axis marks and numbers to make the plot simple
  • Uses theme() with element_blank()
  • This code removes the tick marks (the little lines) and the numbers on the y-axis.
  • I think it makes the plot look cleaner if you donât need to show exact values. Sometimes you might want a plot without extra details to focus only on the overall data.
p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot()

p2 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank())

p3 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(axis.ticks = element_blank(), axis.text.y = element_blank())

p4 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = NULL)

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, p4, ncol = 4,
             top = 'Removing Tick Marks and Labels')

10.Changing the Text of Tick Labels

  • Using scale_y_continuous(labels = â¦) to changes y-axis numbers into words like âTinyâ or âMediumâ
library(gcookbook)

p1 <- ggplot(heightweight, aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn)) +
  geom_point()

p2 <- ggplot(heightweight, aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = c(50, 56, 60, 66, 72),
    labels = c("Tiny", "Really\nshort", "Short", "Medium", "Tallish")
  )

# Add title
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
             top = 'Changing the Text of Tick Labels')

11.Lower Tallish to include 6 people

  • Changes the tick mark range to include more points for âTallishâ, so that it includes more people (for example, it changes the range of the y-axis to include a height of 69).
  • Updates the positions with breaks = â¦.
  • By adjusting the tick marks, you can make sure the labels fit the data better.
p1 <- ggplot(heightweight, aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn)) +
  geom_point()

p2 <- ggplot(heightweight, aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = c(50, 56, 60, 66, 69),
    labels = c("Tiny", "Really\nshort", "Short", "Medium", "Tallish")
  )

# Add title
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
             top = 'Lower Tallish to include 6 people')

12.Changing the Appearance of Tick Labels

  • Uses element_text() to change the angle and position
pg_plot <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_x_discrete(
    breaks = c("ctrl", "trt1", "trt2"),
    labels = c("Control", "Treatment 1", "Treatment 2")
  )
p1 <- pg_plot
p2 <- pg_plot +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = .5))
p3 <- pg_plot +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 3,
             top = 'Changing the Appearance of Tick Labels')

13. Changing the Text of Axis Labels

  • The grid.arrange() function displays both plots side by side for comparison.
hw_plot <- ggplot(heightweight, aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn, colour = sex)) +
  geom_point()

p1 <- hw_plot
p2 <- hw_plot +
  xlab('Age in years') +
  ylab('Height in inches')

grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
             top = 'Changing the Text of Axis Labels')

14. Removing Axis Labels

p1 <- ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot()

p2 <- p1  +
  xlab(NULL)

grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
             top = 'Removing Axis Labels')

15. Changing the Appearance of Axis Labels

-axis.title.x = element_text(...) is to specify that we modifythe x-axis title.

p1 <- ggplot(heightweight, aes(x = ageYear, y = heightIn)) +
  geom_point()
p2 <- p1 +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(face = "italic", colour = "darkred", 
                                    size = 14))
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2,
             top = 'Changing the Appearance of Axis Labels')
